value.value: The portion of the biliary tract outside the liver; the common hepatic duct joins the cystic duct to form the common bile duct.
Any accessory organ of the eye, including the eyelids, eyebrows, lacrimal apparatus, or conjunctiva.
The arched strip of hair on the bony ridge above each eye socket.
Anyone of the short hairs that grow on the edge of the eyelid.
A synovial joint between two adjacent vertebrae. The facet joint links the articular process of one vertebra and the inferior articular process of the adjacent vertebra.
An artery arising from the external carotid artery supplying blood to the surface of the face.
A vein in the face accompanying the facial artery that is a direct continuation of the angular vein and ultimately empties into the internal jugular vein.
Upper abdominal discomfort associated with an urge to vomit.
The back surface, which is in contact with the vitreous humor, of the crystalline lens in the eye.
A fibrillar actin polymer.
A broad, thin, crescent-shaped fold consisting of two layers of peritoneum extending from the notch of the anterior margin of the liver to the anterior abdominal wall and diaphragm.
One of two folds of a mucous membrane spanning the larynx. The two folds aid in breathing and preventing regurgitation to a greater extent than producing sounds.
A small triangular process of dura matter beginning at the internal occipital crest just beneath the tentorium and projecting forward.
A small bundle of nerve fibers that is more or less associated functionally.
A muscle fiber that is able to hydrolyze ATP and transmit electrochemical signals rapidly.

label.value: Female Genital System Fluid or Secretion

value.value: Expelling the contents of the stomach and the sensations associated with it. They are symptoms of an underlying disease or condition and not a specific illness.
A fold of skin covering the tip of the clitoris.
The 1.5 inch long tube carrying urine from the bladder to the outside of the body exiting between the clitoris and vagina.
Any artery arising from the femoral artery.
An oval, membrane covered opening from the tympanic cavity of the middle ear to the vestibule of the inner ear.
An opening into the cochlea of the inner ear that allows for fluid within the cochlea to move.

A type of capillary that is characterized by the presence of circular pores that penetrate the endothelium covered with a continuous basal lamina, and is most commonly found in the intestinal mucosa, renal glomeruli, pancreas, and endocrine glands.
Fibrillin-1 (2871 aa, ~312 kDa) is encoded by the human FBN1 gene. This protein is involved in connective tissue structure.
A filamentous extracellular structure that is rich in the glycoprotein, fibrillin-1, and found in connective tissues where it can act as a scaffold for elastin.
A glycosylated elastic protein produced by the cleavage of fibrinogen by the protease thrombin during blood coagulation.
Connective tissue with fibrous and cartilaginous components.

Mucin is expressed by most glandular epithelia.  Tandem repeats characterize the core mucin protein, apomucin; variation of the protein derives from variation in the number of expressed repeats.  Native forms of mucin are distinct in size and degree of glycosylation; factors other than the primary structure of apomucin may contribute to these characteristics.  Many complex O-linked oligosaccharides are presumably added by glycosyltransferases.  Expression is increased in the lactating breast and in breast, ovary, lung, and prostate malignancies.  It is a serum marker for breast cancer.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the neck region.
A neuroglial cell of ectodermic origin having long, thin, infrequently branched cytoplasmic processes containing numerous fibrillar structures. It is found mainly in the white matter of the brain.
A thin layer of strong fibroareolar tissue beneath the serous coat covering the entire surface of the liver.
A normal variant CSF filled cavity in the brain situated between the leaves of the septum pellucidum. Also called cavum septi pellucidum.
A group of three types of polymeric protein structures that impart shape to a cell and are involved in cellular motility, organelle localization and vesicular targeting.
The most numerous type of lingual papillae, which covers most of the front two thirds of the tongue, and do not contain taste buds.
A slender projection of the plasma membrane at the leading edge of migrating cells. This protrusion contains bundles of long, crosslinked actin filaments.
A fringe like structure.

label.value: Fimbriated End of the Fallopian Tube

value.value: The fringed end of the fallopian tube.
Any of the digits of the hand.
The nail at the end of a finger.

A tumor that has spread from its original (primary) site of growth to another site, close to or distant from the primary site.  Metastasis is characteristic of advanced malignancies, but in rare instances can be seen in neoplasms lacking malignant morphology.
The proximal portion of the duodenum, the first section of the small intestines connected to the stomach.
The posterior portion of the longitudinal fissure on the surface of the liver which separates the left lobe from the lobe of Spigelius and lodges the ductus venosus in the fetus.
A groove or cleft on the surface of the gallbladder extending from the right portal vein to the gallbladder fossa.

label.value: Fissure of the Inferior Vena Cava

value.value: A short deep groove extending upwards from the lobus caudatus in the liver and lodges the vena cava.

The deepest and most prominent groove on the lateral surface of the brain beginning at the anterior perforated substance that runs back and slightly upwards. The fissure of Sylvius, also known as the lateral cerebral sulcus, separates the frontal and parietal lobes from the temporal lobe.
A bone that has a thin and flattened shape.
